BACKGROUND: Cognitive decline is one of the most prominent healthcare issues of 
the 21st century. Within the context of combating cognitive decline through 
behavioural interventions, physical activity is a promising approach. There is a 
dearth of health economic data in the area of behavioural interventions for 
dementia prevention. Yet, economic evaluations are essential for providing 
information to policy makers for resource allocation. It is essential we first 
address population and intervention-specific methodological challenges prior to 
building a larger evidence base. We use a cost-utility analysis conducted 
